## Why Architecture Matters for GRC

Something I have been noticing throughout this project is that GRC can feel abstract when it is disconnected from the actual systems being protected. Frameworks, policies, and risk registers are only useful if the people writing them understand what they are writing about. Today felt like an important bridge — moving from the conceptual side of cloud security into the actual technical architecture of the system I am trying to secure.

You cannot identify risks in a system you do not understand. You cannot evaluate compliance controls without knowing what components exist and how they connect. And you cannot communicate meaningfully with an IT team during a risk assessment or audit if you do not have a working picture of what the infrastructure looks like.

Today was about building that picture for OpenMRS on AWS.

---

## What I Worked On Today

OpenMRS is an open-source electronic health records platform used in over 40 countries — particularly in low-resource healthcare settings where commercial EHR systems are not affordable or practical. It stores sensitive patient data including medical histories, diagnoses, medications, and clinical notes. That data is exactly what HIPAA and other healthcare privacy regulations are designed to protect.

When OpenMRS is deployed on AWS, it typically runs across several core services that each play a distinct role in the overall architecture:

**Amazon EC2 — The Application Server**
EC2 provides the virtual server that runs the OpenMRS web application. When a clinician opens a browser and logs into OpenMRS, they are connecting to an EC2 instance. This is where the application code lives and where user requests are processed. From a security perspective, EC2 is one of the highest-risk components — it is internet-facing, it runs software that needs to be kept patched, and it is the primary entry point for anyone trying to access the system.

**Amazon RDS — The Database**
RDS hosts the patient database — the actual records, clinical notes, and health information that OpenMRS manages. This is the most sensitive component in the entire architecture. A breach of the RDS database is a breach of patient data. The database should never be directly accessible from the internet — it should only be reachable from the EC2 application server through a controlled, private network connection.

**Amazon S3 — Backups and File Storage**
S3 stores backups of the database and any documents or files associated with patient records. S3 is highly reliable and durable — which makes it a good choice for backup storage. But as I covered on Day 16, S3 misconfiguration is one of the most common causes of cloud data exposures. Backup data is just as sensitive as live data — an S3 bucket containing an OpenMRS database backup contains the same patient information as the live database, and it needs to be protected with the same level of care.

**VPC and Security Groups — Network Security**
A Virtual Private Cloud (VPC) is a logically isolated network environment within AWS where the OpenMRS components live. Security groups act as virtual firewalls — they control which traffic is allowed to reach each component. Properly configured security groups are one of the most important security controls in the entire architecture. They determine who can reach the EC2 instance, whether the database is exposed to the internet, and how components communicate with each other internally.

**HTTPS — Encrypted Communication**
All traffic between users' browsers and the OpenMRS application should be encrypted using HTTPS. Without HTTPS, credentials and patient data transmitted over the network could be intercepted. This is both a basic security requirement and a HIPAA technical safeguard obligation.

