## A Real-World Example That Made This Click

While researching today's topic I came across the **2021 Scripps Health ransomware attack** — a significant incident affecting one of the largest healthcare systems in San Diego. The attack took Scripps Health's network offline for nearly a month, forcing staff to use paper records, diverting some patients to other facilities, and disrupting care for hundreds of thousands of patients.

The full technical details of the attack were not entirely public, but post-incident reporting indicated that the attackers gained initial access and then moved laterally through the network before deploying ransomware across multiple systems simultaneously. Scripps Health ultimately notified approximately 147,000 patients that their data may have been exposed.

What this case illustrates from an architecture perspective is the importance of **network segmentation** — keeping different components isolated so that a compromise of one does not automatically lead to a compromise of everything else. In a well-architected AWS deployment, the VPC and security group configuration should ensure that an attacker who compromises the EC2 application server cannot directly reach the RDS database without going through additional controls, and cannot access backup data in S3 without specific permissions.

That is not a perfect defense — a sufficiently privileged attacker can work around segmentation. But it significantly raises the cost and complexity of an attack, and it limits the blast radius of a successful compromise. The Scripps Health incident is a reminder that architecture decisions are security decisions — and they need to be made thoughtfully.

